## querySelector()

Modern JavaScript introduced a much more powerful method: **`querySelector()`**.

Instead of searching explicitly by ID or Class, you just pass it a standard **CSS Selector** (exactly the same way you style things using `.css` files!).

```javascript
// Pass a # to find an ID
let loginBtn = document.querySelector("#login-btn");

// Pass a . to find a Class
let firstCard = document.querySelector(".card");

// Pass nothing to search by raw HTML Tag!
let firstParagraph = document.querySelector("p");
```

## querySelectorAll()

Standard `querySelector()` is lazy. It scans the page, grabs the absolute **FIRST** match it finds, and completely ignores the rest.

If you want a list of EVERY item that matches the CSS selector, you must use **`querySelectorAll()`**.

```javascript
// Returns a NodeList (an Array!) of ALL items with this class
let allCards = document.querySelectorAll(".card");

// Because it acts like an Array, we can loop it!
allCards.forEach((card) => {
  console.log(card);
});
```
